I. Abstract\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi960\sl640\qj\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf3 This paper studied the association of foreign aid to economic growth in Sub-Sahara African (SSA) Countries. Since there are multiple types of foreign aid, I exploit the Official Development Assistance (ODA), known as foreign aid that is used for sustainable economic development. I used Ordinary Least Square (OLS) to regress GDP on Aid, trade, capital formation, and unemployment rate separately for SSA landlocked countries and coastal countries, and in a model that include all SSA countries (landlocked and coastal), while accounting for countries geographic diversity. I found that 1% increase in foreign aid decreases real GDP by 4.8% for SSA countries regardless of their level of development. This paper also highlighted the fact that countries\'92 geographic location, landlocked or costal has a different magnitude of the effect of foreign aid. The results showed that the effect is larger for landlocked compared to coastal countries. Moreover, the effect of aid is 0.019 percentage point higher for landlocked compared to coastal countries.\
\
